          <exercise>
            <title>A question about the slope-intercept form of the equation of a line</title>
                <statement>
                  <p>
                    Determine the slope-intercept form of the equation of the line that passes through
                    the points <m>(2,-2)</m> and <m>(0,3)</m>.  Use the Desmos graph to confirm your
                    equation.
                  </p> 
                </statement>
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    We begin by using the formula <m>m=\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}</m>.
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    <m>m=\frac{3-(-2)}{0-2}=-\frac{5}{2}</m>
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    We know that the <m>y</m>-intercept is <m>(0,3)</m>, so the slope-intercept
                    equation for the line is <m>y=-\frac{5}{2}x+3</m>.
                  </p>
                </solution>
          </exercise> 

          <exercise>
            <title>A question about the slope-intercept form of the equation of a line</title>
                <statement>
                  <p>
                    Suppose that we were asked to determine the slope-intercept equation of the line that passes through the points <m>(3,-2)</m> and <m>(-5,2)</m>.  What approach might we take? 
                  </p>
                  <p>
                      We could begin by using the formula <m>m=\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}</m> to determine that the slope
                      of the line is <m>-\frac{1}{2}</m>.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      We don't directly know the <m>y</m>-intercept of the line, but from the slope we know
                      that the equation of the line is <m>y=-\frac{1}{2}x+b</m> where <m>b</m> is the 
                      <m>y</m>-coordinate of the <m>y</m>-intercept.  So we could substitute the coordinates of the ordered pair <m>(3,-2)</m> into that equation which would give us <m>-2=(-\frac{1}{2})(3)+b</m>, and solving for <m>b</m> we would get <m>-\frac{1}{2}</m>, so the slope-intercept equation for the line is <m>y=-\frac{1}{2}x-\frac{1}{2}</m>.  Note that we could also have used the ordered pair <m>(-5,2)</m> to determine the value of <m>b</m>.
                    </p>
                  <sidebyside widths="67% 27%" margins="0%">
                    <p>
                      Now it's your turn.  Determine the slope-intercept equation for the line that passes through 
                      the points shown in <xref ref="table-3-1">Table</xref>.
                    </p>

                    <table xml:id="table-3-1">
                      <caption></caption>
                        <tabular>
                          <col halign="center" />
                          <col halign="center"/>
                          <row bottom="medium">
                            <cell>
                              <line><m>x</m></line>
                            </cell>
                            <cell>
                              <line><m>y</m></line>
                            </cell>
                          </row>
                          <row>
                            <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>-7</m></cell>
                          </row>
                          <row>
                            <cell><m>-3</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>8</m></cell>
                          </row>
                        </tabular>
                      </table>
                    </sidebyside> 
                  </statement>
                  <solution>
                    <p>
                      We begin by using the formula <m>m=\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}</m> to determine that the slope
                      of the line is <m>-3</m>.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      We don't directly know the <m>y</m>-intercept of the line, but from the slope we know
                      that the equation of the line is <m>y=-3x+b</m> where <m>b</m> is the 
                      <m>y</m>-coordinate of the <m>y</m>-intercept.  Substituting the coordinates of the ordered pair <m>(2,-7)</m> into that equation gives us <m>-7=(-3)(2)+b</m>, and solving for <m>b</m> we get
                      <m>-1</m>, so the slope-intercept equation for the line is <m>y=-3x-1</m>.  Note that we could also have used the ordered pair <m>(-3,8)</m> to determine the
                      value of <m>b</m>.
                    </p>
                 </solution>
          </exercise> 

          <exercise>
            <title>A question about the slope-intercept form of the equation of a line</title>
                <statement>
                  <sidebyside widths="67% 27%" margins="0%">
                    <p>
                      Determine the slope-intercept equation for the line that passes through 
                      the points shown in <xref ref="table-3-2">Table</xref>.
                    </p>

                    <table xml:id="table-3-2">
                      <caption></caption>
                        <tabular>
                          <col halign="center" />
                          <col halign="center"/>
                          <row bottom="medium">
                            <cell>
                              <line><m>x</m></line>
                            </cell>
                            <cell>
                              <line><m>y</m></line>
