           <exercise>
            <title>A question about linear behavior</title>
                <statement>
                  <sidebyside widths="67% 27%" margins="0%">
                    <p>
                      Explain why the three points shown in <xref ref="table-3-3">Table</xref>
                      cannot possibly all lie on the same line.
                    </p>

                    <table xml:id="table-3-3">
                      <caption></caption>
                        <tabular>
                          <col halign="center" />
                          <col halign="center"/>
                          <row bottom="medium">
                            <cell>
                              <line><m>x</m></line>
                            </cell>
                            <cell>
                              <line><m>y</m></line>
                            </cell>
                          </row>
                          <row>
                            <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>7</m></cell>
                          </row>
                          <row>
                            <cell><m>5</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>12</m></cell>
                          </row>
                          <row>
                            <cell><m>8</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>19</m></cell>
                          </row>
                        </tabular>
                      </table>
                    </sidebyside> 
                  </statement>
                  <solution>
                    <p>
                      The line that passes through the first two points has a slope of <m>\frac{5}{3}</m> 
                      whereas the line that passes through the first and third point has a slope of
                      <m>2</m>.  If the points all lied on the same line, we would get the same slope
                      no matter which two points we used in the slope formula. 
                    </p>
                  </solution>
          </exercise> 
 
